summaries.title: First-Generation Challenges in Navigating University Systems
summaries.summaryText: Maria described difficulty understanding financial aid processes and navigating academic advising resources. She relied heavily on peer networks and informal guidance, noting that the institutional language often assumed prior family familiarity with college systems. [Part 1/4]

summaries.title: Recognizing Privilege and Peer Disparities in Engineering Education
summaries.summaryText: Ethan discussed observing classmates who struggled to access tutoring or networking opportunities. His reflection on his own privilege as a continuing-generation student led him to advocate for more peer tutoring support and accessible design lab hours. [Part 2/4]

summaries.title: Developing Academic Confidence Through Mentorship
summaries.summaryText: Daniel described feeling initially out of place in rigorous electrical engineering courses, particularly when comparing himself to peers with prior robotics or coding experience. His confidence improved after joining a peer mentoring program where upperclassmen provided guidance and reassurance. [Part 2/4]

summaries.title: Building Community Through Cultural Organizations
summaries.summaryText: Participation in SHPE and campus cultural centers provided Maria a sense of belonging and identity affirmation. These communities offered emotional support and mentorship that she could not easily find in her department. [Part 1/4]

summaries.title: Balancing Research and Cultural Expectations
summaries.summaryText: Priya balanced heavy research commitments with cultural obligations, feeling pressure to excel as a first-gen Indian-American student in tech. [Part 2/4]

summaries.title: Building Inclusive Engineering Teams
summaries.summaryText: Ethan noted that successful project outcomes often came from teams with diverse backgrounds and perspectives. He believes empathy and active listening should be core engineering competencies. [Part 1/4]

areasForImprovement.title: Expand Visibility of First-Gen Student Resources
areasForImprovement.description: Current communication about financial aid, academic advising, and mentorship resources does not adequately reach first-generation students. Improving targeted outreach through orientation and department emails could reduce inequities in access to support. [Extended 1]
actionItems: Add first-gen resource links to department portals

areasForImprovement.title: Broaden Access to Early Engineering Exposure Programs
areasForImprovement.description: Ethan’s reflection highlights unequal early access to STEM exposure. Partnering with local schools and community programs can help level the playing field for underrepresented groups. [Extended 2]
actionItems: Create summer bridge programs for high school students
Offer needs-based scholarships for pre-college engineering camps

areasForImprovement.title: Enhance First-Gen Orientation Programs
areasForImprovement.description: Provide stronger academic transition support for first-generation students entering engineering. [Extended 4]

areasForImprovement.title: Integrate Wellness Programming into STEM Curriculum
areasForImprovement.description: Develop optional workshops or credit modules linking mental health and STEM performance. [Extended 4]

areasForImprovement.title: Increase Mentorship for Women in Computing
areasForImprovement.description: Expand mentorship and career guidance for women and first-gen students. [Extended 4]

areasForImprovement.description: Develop optional workshops or credit modules linking mental health and STEM performance. [Extended 2]

areasForImprovement.title: Increase Cultural Representation in Engineering Programs
areasForImprovement.description: Students emphasized the importance of seeing role models and mentors from similar cultural backgrounds. Faculty partnerships with student cultural organizations could foster inclusion and belonging. [Extended 1]
actionItems: Integrate cultural competence into departmental events

areasForImprovement.title: Formal Recognition for Student Advocacy and Mentorship Work
areasForImprovement.description: Students like Aaliyah contribute substantial unpaid labor in mentoring and advocacy roles. Institutions should recognize these contributions as part of leadership and service learning frameworks. [Extended 4]
actionItems: Create service-learning credit for mentorship and advocacy roles
Include advocacy experience in leadership award criteria
